Details
1. Signature and return contract
- Syntax: Number.isInteger(value)
- Parameter: value — any ECMAScript value
- Return: boolean — true if value is a Number that is finite and has no fractional component; otherwise false.

2. Precise type and range checks
- Implementation checklist: typeof value must be 'number'; value must not be NaN nor ±Infinity; check that Math.floor(value) === value (or value % 1 === 0) to assert integerness.
- Exact spec reference: ECMAScript Number.isInteger section.

3. Precision and edge-cases
- Due to IEEE-754 double precision, very large numeric literals may lose fractional precision and falsely appear as integers. Examples: 5.0000000000000001 -> stored as 5 -> Number.isInteger returns true.
- Values larger than Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER may lose precision; test behavior when exact integer comparisons are required.

4. Polyfill guidance
- Polyfill pseudocode (behavioral):
  - if (typeof value !== 'number') return false;
  - if (!isFinite(value)) return false;
  - return Math.floor(value) === value;
- When providing a polyfill in older environments, prefer using Number.isFinite checks and Math.trunc where available.

Supplementary details
- Use Number.isInteger for strict integer validation prior to using integer-only algorithms (array indexing, loop counts).
- For user-facing input parsing, combine Number.isInteger with additional range checks (e.g., 1 <= n <= max) and explicit error messages.

Reference details (exact API)
- Number.isInteger(value) -> boolean
- Accepts any value; returns true only for finite Number primitives with no fractional part.

